programme.desc: On this week's show we catch up with Owen Reigler in Southern Iowa who shares a few tips and strategies as gun seasons enter the fold across the country. Next, we head to Southern Illinois with Chad Holmes for a bow hunt on the day before the state's opening day of gun season. Experiencing the full force of the peak rut, Chad no sooner climbs out of his stand for the morning than hears a chase headed straight for him. The following day, his son Casen Holmes heads to a Redneck blind hoping to cash in on opening day of the Illinois firearms season. After that, we catch up with David Williams and Andy Melton who also gear up for the gun opener in Illinois. Hoping to key in on historical hot spots during the lockdown phase on their farms, the guys find themselves with back to back opportunities to fill their gun tags on two mature bucks. Looking forward, the team still has some awesome stories to share with you so be sure to stay tuned in as we move through the month of December. Thank you as always for your support!

programme.title: The Perfect Bow Hunt, Drake's Biggest 8 Point Buck Ever

One that ended with him sitting behind a 23"+ wide Iowa giant, we start at the beginning and jump on the roller coaster ride that shows the highest of highs and lowest of lows. Tag along as we enjoy heart pounding ground encounters, a perfect heart shot, and everything in between during this epic chase. As always, we appreciate the continued support and hope you've had a great season of your own! Don't forget the Chasing November give away is still active and entry is simple. Follow the link below and sign up to win some incredible prizes!

programme.title: 177" Giant Buck At 10 Yards On The Ground, A One In A Million Hunting Season
programme.desc: On this week's episode of Midwest Whitetail, we take a deep dive into one of the most epic single season stories ever captured in the whitetail woods. A roller coaster filled with the lowest of lows to the highest of highs, we couldn't be more excited to share this one with you. Kaleb Greiner entered the 2023 hunting season with high hopes but he could have never predicted what followed next. Between stacking up a hitlist that included 3 bucks over 175", an EHD outbreak that decimates the deer heard, and a face to face 10 yard bow shot with a 177" giant, this is the story of Kaleb's one in a million hunting season here in Iowa.

programme.title: Giant Rut-Crazed River Farm Buck At 5 Yards, Mike's Best Bow Hunting Strategies
programme.desc: On this week's episode, we sit down with Mike Reed in Iowa as he takes us through the story of yet another River Farm legend he calls "Fitzmagic." With encounters dating back to the early days of hunting the river bottom in 2019, Mike dissects the buck's patterns and the area in which he lived that ultimately led to getting an opportunity at the 7.5 year old brute. Mike dives into multiple stand locations spanning the newer addition to the main River Farm, what he has learned over the past few years of hunting the area and many more lessons learned along the way. We hope you enjoy and be sure to tune in over the coming weeks as we continue to bring more awesome hunt action your way! Thank you as always for the support.

programme.title: Two Perfect Hunts With The Reed Family, Reading The Christmas Story
programme.desc: On this week's episode of Midwest Whitetail, we bring you a show that has a little bit of everything. Kicking things off, we join Chad Holmes who reads us the Christmas Story and discusses the true meaning of Christmas. Following that we join Mike and Bella Reed who bring us up to speed on what has been happening in the woods since Mike tagged out on "Fitzmagic" back in November. Finally, we join the Reed family during the shotgun seasons as two perfect hunts unfold on the same bean field. Up first is Kathryn Reed who makes it to the woods for her first hunt of the year. With the wrong wind direction to hunt the current Redneck Blind setup, Mike gets mobile and moves a trailer blind into place. The move pays off BIG and Kathryn has the perfect hunt and builds another memory. Then, we jump to the same field only a few days later with Brynn Reed who's hoping to pull off the same feat as her mom! Little did she know the biggest buck of her life would walk into the field and after following her shooting process, a perfectly placed bullet closes the chapter on a true surprise buck. As always, thank you from all of us at Midwest Whitetail for taking the time to watch and for supporting us this entire season. Merry Christmas to each and every one of you and good luck the next time you hit the woods!

programme.title: Handmade: A Tribute to DIY Shaper
programme.desc: For most of us, there’s a lot of guesswork that goes into picking our surfboards. We’re drawn to certain curves, edges, channels, tail shapes that remind us of something that worked for us before, or spark our curiosity about what could work for us the next time we paddle out. But nothing cuts down the guesswork and helps us really understand the dynamics of what’s going on underfoot like making a board yourself. Sure, the first, second, maybe even 134th board you make might not be as pretty as something you could pull off the rack of a surf shop, but it surely teaches you a lot more, and connects you more deeply to your surfing. Last fall, we rallied some of our favorite surfers who make and ride their own sticks, put them in an improvised shaping bay together (a barn in Northern California) and documented them tearing into foam. Between passes with the planer, we asked them for their take on self-shaping boards, what it teaches you and how it can come to define your relationship with surfing. It was enlightening, and also a hell of a lot of fun. After six days, a dozen blanks, many beers and one destroyed Mickey Mouse piñata, the crew had a handful of beautiful new surfcraft to try, which they did, in waves all over the world. “Handmade” is a tribute to surfing’s DIYers, and a celebration of the connection between surfers and their surfcraft, from the shaping bay to the lineup.

programme.title: Handmade 2: A Journey Through Perfect Waves and Handshaped Boards
programme.desc: On paper, shaping yourself a surfboard by hand would seem like a giant pain in the ass. Shaping bays are small, dusty, sweat-inducing spaces. Planer whirs are not anyone's preferred soundtrack. You'll make a lot of shit surfboards on your way to the first one that rides at all like you want it to. But when you stick it out, the journey changes you and it changes your surfing in some wonderful ways, and you realize that the thing that seemed like such a pain has become something incomparably fun. Case in point: Alex Knost, Ellis Ericson, Andrew Doheny and Shyama Buttonshaw. These four surfers, the stars of the film above, started their handshaping journeys many years ago. And amid all the clouds of foam dust they learned a thing or two about how their equipment works and what feelings they wanted to chase in their surfing. It's had some profound effects on their style of riding waves, but more importantly, they'll be the first to tell you that it's been a ridiculous amount of fun.
